24. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133709" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Odontomachus rufus Jerdon" lsidName-HNS="Odontomachus rufus Jerdon" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufus">Odontomachus rufus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel>N. S</taxonomicNameLabel>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="116">Worker, length l- 4 th of an inch; head bulging at the sides, narrowed in front; eyes of moderate size; anterior antennae rather long, slender; jaws closely approached at their base, long, linear, with three strong pointed teeth at the end; thorax narrow; abdominal pedicle raised, pointed and conic; abdomen long, oval; head, thorax and legs rufous; abdomen dark brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="116">I obtained this Ant under stones in a jungle in the Salem dis-trict, and know nothing of its habits.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="116">I have since obtained one individual also in the Wynaad which may be the Warrior of this species - if the society consist of different individuals. It is 11 - 24 th of an inch long, and appears only to differ, besides its larger size, in having the eyes smaller, and more advanced, the teeth of the jaw blunt, and the thorax finely striated.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
